<ol class="enumerate" id='magicparlabel-23'><li class="enumerate_item">Compute the likelihood in the aforesaid Bayesian model.</li>
<li class="enumerate_item">Show that the sampling distribution is a member of the exponential family.</li>
<li class="enumerate_item">Specify the PDF of the conjugate prior distribution <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mrow>
  <mrow><mo> &Pi; </mo><mo form='prefix' fence='true' stretchy='true' symmetric='true'>(</mo>
<mi> &lambda; </mi>
<mo form='postfix' fence='true' stretchy='true' symmetric='true'>)</mo>

  </mrow>
 </mrow></math> of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mrow><mi> &lambda; </mi>
 </mrow></math>, and identify the parametric family of distributions as <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mrow>
  <mrow><mi> &lambda; </mi><mo> &sim; </mo>
   <mstyle mathvariant='normal'>
    <mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>a</mi>
    </mrow>
   </mstyle><mo form='prefix' fence='true' stretchy='true' symmetric='true'>(</mo>

   <mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>b</mi>
   </mrow>
<mo form='postfix' fence='true' stretchy='true' symmetric='true'>)</mo>

  </mrow>
 </mrow></math>, with <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mrow>
  <mrow><mi>a</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn>
  </mrow>
 </mrow></math>, and <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mrow>
  <mrow><mi>b</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>0</mn>
  </mrow>
 </mrow></math>. While you are deriving the conjugate prior distribution of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mrow><mi> &lambda; </mi>
 </mrow></math>, discuss which of the prior hyper-parameters can be considered as the `strength of the prior information and which can be considered as summarizing the prior information.</li>
<li class="enumerate_item">Compute the PDF of the posterior distribution of <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mrow><mi> &lambda; </mi>
 </mrow></math>, identify the posterior distribution as a Gamma distribution <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mrow>
  <mrow>
   <mstyle mathvariant='normal'>
    <mrow><mi>G</mi><mi>a</mi>
    </mrow>
   </mstyle><mo form='prefix' fence='true' stretchy='true' symmetric='true'>(</mo>

   <mrow>
    <mover>
     <mrow><mi>a</mi>
     </mrow><mo stretchy="true">&tilde;</mo>
    </mover><mo>,</mo>
    <mover>
     <mrow><mi>b</mi>
     </mrow><mo stretchy="true">&tilde;</mo>
    </mover>
   </mrow>
<mo form='postfix' fence='true' stretchy='true' symmetric='true'>)</mo>

  </mrow>
 </mrow></math>, and compute the posterior hyper-parameters <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mrow>
  <mover>
   <mrow><mi>a</mi>
   </mrow><mo stretchy="true">&tilde;</mo>
  </mover>
 </mrow></math>, and <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mrow>
  <mover>
   <mrow><mi>b</mi>
   </mrow><mo stretchy="true">&tilde;</mo>
  </mover>
 </mrow></math>.</li>
<li class="enumerate_item">Compute the PMF of the predictive distribution of a future outcome <math xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML">
 <mrow>
  <mrow><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo>
   <msub>
    <mrow><mi>x</mi>
    </mrow>
    <mrow>
     <mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn>
     </mrow>
    </mrow>
   </msub><mo>,</mo>
  </mrow>
 </mrow></math> identify the name of the resulting predictive distribution, and compute its parameters.</li>
</ol>


